05086nam a22007695i 9780801465659DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979753337  a97808014656597 a10.7591/97808014656592doi  a(DE-B1597)478254  a(OCoLC)961614534  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN3448.B54bB64 2016 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a809.393542231 aBoes, Tobias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFormative Fictions :bNationalism, Cosmopolitanism, and the Bildungsroman /cTobias Boes. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Translations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Methodological Background -- t1. The Limits of National Form: Normativity and Performativity in Bildungsroman Criticism -- t2. Apprenticeship of the Novel: Goethe and the Invention of History -- tPart II. Comparative Studies -- t3. Epigonal Consciousness: Stendhal, Immermann, and the "Problem of Generations" around 1830 -- t4. Long-Distance Fantasies: Freytag, Eliot, and National Literature in the Age of Empire -- t5. Urban Vernaculars: Joyce, Döblin, and the "Individuating Rhythm" of Modernity -- tConclusion: Apocalipsis cum figuris : Thomas Mann and the Bildungsroman at the Ends of Time -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Bildungsroman, or "novel of formation," has long led a paradoxical life within literary studies, having been construed both as a peculiarly German genre, a marker of that country's cultural difference from Western Europe, and as a universal expression of modernity. In Formative Fictions, Tobias Boes argues that the dual status of the Bildungsroman renders this novelistic form an elegant way to negotiate the diverging critical discourses surrounding national and world literature.Since the late eighteenth century, authors have employed the story of a protagonist's journey into maturity as a powerful tool with which to facilitate the creation of national communities among their readers. Such attempts always stumble over what Boes calls "cosmopolitan remainders," identity claims that resist nationalism's aim for closure in the normative regime of the nation-state. These cosmopolitan remainders are responsible for the curiously hesitant endings of so many novels of formation.In Formative Fictions, Boes presents readings of a number of novels-Goethe's Wilhelm Meister's Apprenticeship, Karl Leberecht Immermann's The Epigones, Gustav Freytag's Debit and Credit, Alfred Döblin's Berlin Alexanderplatz, and Thomas Mann's Doctor Faustus among them-that have always been felt to be particularly "German" and compares them with novels by such authors as George Eliot and James Joyce to show that what seem to be markers of national particularity can productively be read as topics of world literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBildungsromansxHistory and criticism. 0aCity and town life in literature. 0aComparative literaturexEuropean and German. 0aComparative literaturexGerman and European. 0aEuropean fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aNationalism and literature. 4aEurope. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801465659zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801465659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt